"# Chapter 3 — Hash Tables

A hash table is a shape that lets you say 'given this key, give me
that value' in constant time. Motoi supports the SRFI-125 hash-table
family and provides two names for the most common operations —
`hash-table-ref`/`hash-table-set!` (canonical) and `hash-ref`/`hash-set!`
(the shorthand Sakura's substrate uses).

## Why hash tables exist

Lists are great when you walk them front to back. But if you want
to answer 'what's the age of Alice?' by looking up 'Alice', walking
the list every time is slow. Hash tables let you jump straight to
the answer.

Under the hood the shape is: hash the key, use the hash as an index
into an internal table, find the value. Motoi wraps that inside a
`HashTable` object; you never see the internals, just the verbs.

## Problem 1 — A simple key-value store

Build a hash table, put values in, read them out.

```
(define ages (make-hash-table))

(hash-table-set! ages 'alice 30)
(hash-table-set! ages 'bob 25)
(hash-table-set! ages 'carol 35)

(display (hash-table-ref ages 'alice #f))
;; => 30

(display (hash-table-ref ages 'dave 'unknown))
;; => unknown
```

Read the shape. `make-hash-table` returns an empty table.
`hash-table-set! table key value` mutates the table.
`hash-table-ref table key default` returns the value, or the default
if the key is missing.

## Problem 2 — Count with hash-table-update!

`hash-table-update!` reads a key, applies a function to the current
value, and writes back the result. Optional third argument is the
default for when the key is missing.

```
(define counts (make-hash-table))

(define (bump! k)
  (hash-table-update! counts k (lambda (v) (+ v 1)) 0))

(bump! 'apple)
(bump! 'banana)
(bump! 'apple)
(bump! 'apple)

(display (hash-table-ref counts 'apple #f))
;; => 3
(display (hash-table-ref counts 'banana #f))
;; => 1
```

`bump!` says: whatever the value of `k` is, add one; if `k` is
missing, start from 0. That is a histogram in three lines.

## Problem 3 — Walk the table

`hash-table-keys` gives you the keys, `hash-table-values` gives you
the values, `hash-table-size` gives you the count.

```
(define scores (make-hash-table))
(hash-table-set! scores 'alice 85)
(hash-table-set! scores 'bob 92)
(hash-table-set! scores 'carol 78)

(display (hash-table-size scores))
;; => 3

(for-each (lambda (k)
            (display k)
            (display \": \")
            (display (hash-table-ref scores k #f))
            (display \"\\n\"))
          (hash-table-keys scores))
;; => alice: 85
;;    bob: 92
;;    carol: 78
;;   (order unspecified)
```

Notice the caveat: hash tables don't preserve insertion order.
If you need order, sort the keys before you walk.

## Problem 4 (expert) — Fold to summarize

`hash-table-fold` walks every key-value pair with an accumulator.
This is the shape for summing, averaging, or building a derived
value from the table.

```
(define prices (make-hash-table))
(hash-table-set! prices 'apple 1.50)
(hash-table-set! prices 'banana 0.75)
(hash-table-set! prices 'cherry 3.00)

(define total
  (hash-table-fold prices
                    (lambda (k v acc) (+ v acc))
                    0))

(display total)
;; => 5.25
```

`hash-table-fold` takes the table, a folder `(lambda (key value accumulator) ...)`,
and the initial accumulator. Every key-value pair gets folded in.

## Capstone — A word-frequency counter

Given a list of words, count how often each appears. Sort by count.

```
(define words (list 'the 'quick 'brown 'fox
                     'the 'lazy 'dog
                     'the 'quick 'fox))

(define freq (make-hash-table))

(for-each (lambda (w)
            (hash-table-update! freq w (lambda (v) (+ v 1)) 0))
          words)

(define alist (hash-table->alist freq))
(display alist)
;; => ((the 3) (quick 2) (fox 2) (brown 1) (lazy 1) (dog 1))
;;   (order unspecified — sort if it matters)
```

The chain reads left-to-right: for each word, bump its counter; when
done, convert to an alist for display or further sorting. `hash-table->alist`
is the escape hatch when you're done with the table and want a list.

## Alternate name — hash-ref / hash-set!

Sakura's substrate uses `hash-ref` and `hash-set!` as aliases for
`hash-table-ref` and `hash-table-set!`. Both names are installed as
CORE in Motoi so cross-dialect code Just Works:

```
(define h (make-hash-table))
(hash-set! h 'k 42)
(display (hash-ref h 'k #f))
;; => 42
```

Use whichever is comfortable. The Priya 2026-07-18 audit found 636
uses of `hash-ref` in Sakura corpus; both names are canonical now.

## What's next

In Chapter 4 we tackle the string library. Hash tables answered
'how do I find a value by key?'; the string library answers 'how do
I take this text apart and put it back together?'
")
